e scenes in Mexico. An expert work of narrative nonfiction, Exit Wounds provides a rare, intimate look into the world of firearms trafficking and urges us to understand the effects of lax US gun laws abroad. Jusionyte masterfully weaves together the gripping stories of people who live and work with guns north and south of the border: a Mexican businessman who smuggles guns for protection, a teenage girl turned trained assassin, two US federal agents trying to stop gun traffickers, and a journalist who risks his life to report on organized crime. Based on years of fieldwork, Exit Wounds expands current debates about guns in America, grappling with US complicity in violence on both sides of the border.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFirearmszMexican-American Border Region. 0aFirearmszMexico. 0aFirearmszUnited States. 0aGun controlzMexican-American Border Region. 0aIllegal arms transferszMexican-American Border Region. 0aViolencezMexican-American Border RegionxPrevention. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079135840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520395961?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520395961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520395961/original  a978-3-11-079135-8  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles